eccles-tts-packager
===================

NOTE: this file previously described an older/different version of this tool (a different
executable name, a different CLI syntax, a different config file format, and a claimed
dependency on ffmpeg.exe). None of that matched the actual source in eccles/tools/src/, so
this has been rewritten to match what the tool actually does today.

WHAT IT DOES
------------
Scans a folder of .wav files, optionally resamples/converts each one to a common
sample rate / bit depth / channel layout (all done in-process, no external tools like
ffmpeg are used), strips trailing silence if requested, and packs every clip into a single
binary blob (StaticModel.eccles) plus a generated C++ header (StaticModel.h) that the
firmware uses to look clips up by name.

Only STATIC model packaging is implemented. The source has scaffolding for a "dynamic"
model type (ModelType::DYNAMIC in AudioConfig.h, a "-type dynamic" flag, a "type:dynamic"
config key) but there is no DynamicModel class anywhere in this codebase -- selecting it
will make the tool report an error rather than silently doing something else.

BUILDING
--------
The executable name is eccles-tts-packager (eccles-tts-packager.exe on Windows). It's a
plain host-native C++ program with no ESP-IDF/embedded dependencies, built via the
"native" PlatformIO environment declared in the project's platformio.ini:

    pio run -e native

(or compile eccles/tools/src/*.cpp directly with any C++17 compiler). The resulting
binary must be placed at eccles/tools/bin/ for the "-platformIO" invocation described
below to find the resources/output folders correctly.

USAGE
-----
    eccles-tts-packager -platformIO
        Run from eccles/tools/bin/ inside the IDF project. Resolves everything relative to
        the project root: reads eccles/resources/models/*.wav, writes the binary to
        littlefs_image/StaticModel.eccles and the header to
        components/eccles/include/StaticModel.h. This is what execute-tts-packager.py
        (see the project root) invokes automatically as part of the "native" PlatformIO
        build, whenever a file under eccles/resources/models/ changes.

    eccles-tts-packager <wav-folder> [config.txt]
        Run anywhere. Packs every .wav file in <wav-folder> (extension match is
        case-insensitive) and writes StaticModel.eccles / StaticModel.h into the current
        working directory. If a config file path is given (must contain ".txt"), its
        settings are applied; otherwise the defaults below are used.

CONFIG FILE FORMAT
------------------
A plain text file, one "key:value" setting per line. All keys are optional; anything not
set keeps its default.

    raw:1            skip all conversion below entirely and pack every .wav file exactly
                      as-is (bytes untouched). Every file must then already share the same
                      sample rate/depth/channel layout, or packing is rejected.
    rate:<hz>         target sample rate, e.g. rate:16000
    depth:<bits>      target bit depth, e.g. depth:16
    channel:mono|stereo
    tsr:true|false    trailing silence removal
    type:static|dynamic   only "static" is actually implemented (see above)

Defaults if no config file is supplied or a key is omitted:

    rate:8000
    depth:16
    channel:mono
    tsr:true

OUTPUT FORMAT
-------------
StaticModel.eccles is a simple concatenation:

    [ "ECCLES" magic][clip 1 audio bytes][clip 2 audio bytes][clip 3 audio bytes]...

Each clip's own 44-byte .wav header is stripped before its audio bytes are appended;
only the raw PCM payload is stored. StaticModel.h (generated alongside it) declares:

    ECCLES_SAMPLE_RATE / ECCLES_BIT_DEPTH / ECCLES_CHANNELS   the shared format all clips
                                                               were normalized to
    a per-clip entry (offset, size, name) for every packaged file
    a lookup helper the firmware uses to find a clip's offset/size by name

Every packaged clip must end up sharing the exact same sample rate / bit depth / channel
layout (that's the entire point of the config step above) -- the packager checks this
after conversion and refuses to produce output if a clip doesn't match.

